snippet.textDisplay: Wow this review sucks lol. Really liked the movie but I’m always curious about mistakes or lack of logic in screenplays. I stopped watching when the fact that all the clocks in the movie are on 11:11 was simply called a sin without any further reasoning behind it. It‘s in fact probably the biggest hint in the movie, that all of it could possibly just have happened in the protagonist‘s imagination - within a short moment. The audience can‘t know if the whole story really happened, besides the obvious things that Arthur just imagined, of course. And that, for me, makes the movie a great open story with its own ending to everyone who saw it. Again, very poor and subjective review.

I'm all for poking fun at movies, even movies I love, and I'm all for joke sins because in the end it's just a youtube comedy video. But a lot of what your sinning is really lazy.
For example, it IS in the Batman universe. It doesn't really have any obligation to be subtle about that.
Or the complaint about the news shifting from garbage to a poor vs rich protest. It's not a long stretch at all. Firstly, multiple things CAN happen at one time. Secondly, the garbage workers strike insinuates that people who literally pick up the garbage of others aren't paid enough, and no one else is willing to sacrifice that amount of dignity or freedom for such meager pay. It was always a rich vs poor thing.

I can laugh at and enjoy the 'sins' that CinemaSins points out in this movie, and that's okay.
But as someone who lives with a mental illness, I can attest to the movie feeling very true to life in how the world appears to you, and how much of our current society looks down upon and treats people like Arthur Fleck. The movie was by turns both horrifying and exhilarating. It makes for a nearly perfect origin story of how a mentally ill man becomes the Joker.

snippet.textDisplay:
Everyone has their opinions... but as an egotistic, over-analyzing, movie junkie, I should say that you're kind of missing the point of the story. I would explain, but it would take much too long, and if you miss the point... you can't really understand until you have some connection. Me, for instance, I've dealt with my own demons, usually from the hellhole of a town I live in. People like me, are seen as freaks and monsters, but the people who call us that, are our own monsters. To have your own power, or to feel powerful after an adrenaline-fueled action (not murder, of course) is a temporary solution to everything. Suddenly, you aren't alone.

Arthur Fleck isn't really "The Joker" we read about in comic books. He's a guy who sees himself as a hero, who saves everyone from Gotham. Of course, he isn't. He isn't a genius. His whole life is a joke. So, he might not be "The Joker", but he could be someone like him, who's life is a toxic, sad, unending joke. One that he's always the butt of. And unfortunately, everyone is possible of eventually snapping.

Arthur Fleck isn't really "The Joker" we read about in comic books. He's a guy who sees himself as a hero, who saves everyone from Gotham. Of course, he isn't. He isn't a genius. His whole life is a joke.  So, he might not be "The Joker", but he could be someone like him, who's life is a toxic, sad, unending joke. One that he's always the butt of. And unfortunately, everyone is possible of eventually snapping.
